1
00:00:00,233 --> 00:00:28,873
just to remind ourselves and for those of you who are fairly new to this insight meditation vipassana just to go over some of the principles and some of the pitfalls the hindrances that we come across so one of the insights that the Buddha had when he became fully liberated

2
00:00:29,849 --> 00:00:49,216
was that all the floods, I don't know how to translate that, the āsura, these unwholesome dispositions within us had been completely transformed.

3
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:58,270
So there's a process that's going on within our meditation which is beyond our control

4
00:00:58,738 --> 00:01:27,462
beyond our direct control which is this process of transformation when we are experiencing directly what's happening within the heart all these negative states there are five of them we split them up into five so that we could see them more clearly they're not simply dying out

5
00:01:27,983 --> 00:01:32,769
they're also then becoming or turning gently into their opposites.

6
00:01:35,674 --> 00:01:56,504
So when we sit and anything around greed comes up, greed, lust, desire for fame, desire for pleasures of any kind, whenever we feel that searching within us to be happy in some sort of sensual or emotional way,

7
00:01:58,594 --> 00:02:01,459
then that searching is coming from the self.

8
00:02:03,381 --> 00:02:06,185
And the self is just really trying to be happy.

9
00:02:07,746 --> 00:02:08,508
It's sad, really.

10
00:02:09,490 --> 00:02:10,531
It just wants to be happy.

11
00:02:11,472 --> 00:02:14,195
But it just keeps investing in the wrong stock.

12
00:02:14,576 --> 00:02:16,338
That's all.

13
00:02:16,359 --> 00:02:19,362
So it invests in food, sex, drugs, rock and roll.

14
00:02:20,905 --> 00:02:24,490
And it's alright for a while, as you know.

15
00:02:26,673 --> 00:02:27,454
And then it sort of

16
00:02:28,277 --> 00:02:29,758
dissipates, it cracks up.

17
00:02:31,060 --> 00:02:36,004
And that's the sort of basic problem with the happinesses and joys of life.

18
00:02:36,264 --> 00:02:39,548
They're not evil, but they're wonderful.

19
00:02:40,368 --> 00:02:42,670
It's just we have a wrong relationship with them, that's all.

20
00:02:44,012 --> 00:02:48,756
If we can enjoy these things and just let them go, then they don't cause us any problems.

21
00:02:50,176 --> 00:02:54,800
But that attachment, unfortunately, is a natural consequence of the self.

22
00:02:55,741 --> 00:02:57,963
It's its delusion about

23
00:02:58,467 --> 00:02:59,587
the way life is.

24
00:03:03,032 --> 00:03:12,043
And that's why we try to observe these three characteristics, because that undermines that delusion and begins to create a different relationship to the world.

25
00:03:14,806 --> 00:03:26,600
So when we talk about suffering, the word dukkha, that's what it's translating, the word suffering is sometimes too strong for it.

26
00:03:27,052 --> 00:03:33,782
a discontent, a feeling of alienation, a feeling of not fitting, loneliness, all that.

27
00:03:34,584 --> 00:03:36,347
It's all included in this word dukkha.

28
00:03:37,247 --> 00:03:44,018
And included there also is the inability for the pleasures and joys of life to deliver.

29
00:03:45,501 --> 00:03:55,895
So when we're seeking in the wrong place, then at some point there's going to come some feeling of unsatisfactoriness, dissatisfaction.

30
00:03:58,036 --> 00:04:05,625
And when we sit, we can see this vicious circle.

31
00:04:08,027 --> 00:04:15,758
So something comes into the mind, some pleasant thing, and there's a movement towards it, to grab it, to hold it, to develop it, to maintain it.

32
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:23,447
And then something unpleasant comes into the mind, and there's a movement to ignore it, to push it away.

33
00:04:24,408 --> 00:04:25,569
It's too strong, of course.

34
00:04:25,949 --> 00:04:26,810
One wants to run away.

35
00:04:27,043 --> 00:04:29,026
So there you've got your fight-flight syndrome.

36
00:04:31,091 --> 00:04:42,370
So these three emotional positions of attachment, grasping, wanting, and pushing and running come out of this wrong view.

37
00:04:43,432 --> 00:04:50,925
And if you watch yourself during the day, you're constantly running around this little vicious circle.

38
00:04:52,221 --> 00:04:59,468
You might have got up this morning and saw the rain and immediately there's, oh, that's sucky old England.

39
00:04:59,488 --> 00:05:07,437
And then you might have come down later or after meditation and then there's breakfast and, oh, great.

40
00:05:07,456 --> 00:05:10,100
There's a grasping for breakfast.

41
00:05:10,120 --> 00:05:13,442
And then there's a work period, oh, no.

42
00:05:14,564 --> 00:05:21,992
We're constantly emotionally going up and down on this wave, this rather unfortunate wave of wanting, not wanting

43
00:05:23,490 --> 00:05:26,254
And this wanting-not wanting does have a basis.

44
00:05:26,295 --> 00:05:28,778
It has a basis in the way we experience life.

45
00:05:29,459 --> 00:05:31,603
So we experience life as pleasant or unpleasant.

46
00:05:31,862 --> 00:05:32,744
I mean, that's natural.

47
00:05:33,646 --> 00:05:38,552
There are things which the body feels is pleasant, and there are things it feels unpleasant.

48
00:05:38,572 --> 00:05:42,218
So a pleasant taste on the tongue, and when you get a headache, that's not so pleasant.

49
00:05:43,399 --> 00:05:45,723
That doesn't create any problems.

50
00:05:45,742 --> 00:05:51,692
It's the reaction that we have, the inability to stay calm, equanimous, accepting,

51
00:05:52,161 --> 00:05:53,843
with it within our own hearts.

52
00:05:54,904 --> 00:05:58,307
That's where the problem lies.

53
00:05:58,327 --> 00:06:07,877
So, what we're trying to become aware of is, very keenly, is that movement in the mind of wanting, not wanting, and the vicious circle that it creates.

54
00:06:09,377 --> 00:06:15,923
Now, to be aware of that, you have to access a different way of being inside yourself.

55
00:06:17,165 --> 00:06:21,408
You can't join in that circle, you get lost.

56
00:06:22,132 --> 00:06:29,843
so that whenever desire arises you run for it, go for it, so your whole life becomes impelled by that desire.

57
00:06:30,524 --> 00:06:41,000
The better job, the better car, the whole of our economic system is driven on the understanding that you can create people's desires.

58
00:06:42,723 --> 00:06:48,932
I think originally when Smith wrote his book about capitalism, I think he was

59
00:06:49,350 --> 00:07:18,463
I think he thought it would be driven by the consumer but he didn't realize the power of the advertiser and the power of human desire so as soon as you put a pretty picture up everybody wants it so the advertisers know what drives us just fundamental psychology really about greed so

60
00:07:19,321 --> 00:07:28,074
that understanding about pleasure, and then the other side about running away, you see, what we're trying to do is to see that process.

61
00:07:29,014 --> 00:07:31,038
You can't see it when you're lost in it.

62
00:07:31,538 --> 00:07:34,242
You can't see it when you're totally indulgent.

63
00:07:34,863 --> 00:07:36,586
You can't see it when you're totally in a rage.

64
00:07:37,487 --> 00:07:48,483
So somehow you have to access a position where you can observe that, come to know it, come to see it as unskillful, unwholesome, leading only to more unsatisfactoriness,

65
00:07:48,987 --> 00:08:16,175
and then of course you tend to wean yourself off it so now that position of looking if you can think of a comb and at the base of it there's this vicious circle going on and you're sitting on top and you're looking down as it were on this psychology that's wanting not wanting wanting not wanting wanting not wanting and that position there that's the vipassana position

66
00:08:16,882 --> 00:08:19,625
So vipassana just means to see things clearly.

67
00:08:20,086 --> 00:08:23,591
The V is the strengthening and passana, passity, just means to see.

68
00:08:24,072 --> 00:08:27,958
So it's exactly the same as English, to see clearly, to see discriminately.

69
00:08:31,783 --> 00:08:37,711
Now this seeing, this knowing, you see, is what's actually deluded.

70
00:08:38,972 --> 00:08:43,058
It's because we don't see clearly that we get lost in these little traps.

71
00:08:45,142 --> 00:08:46,163
And it's only when you

72
00:08:46,462 --> 00:08:48,924
Turn on what's happening on the mind.

73
00:08:48,945 --> 00:08:51,947
You catch it when you see it.

74
00:08:52,869 --> 00:08:58,173
That suddenly this intelligence we have pulls itself out of that indulgence.

75
00:08:58,673 --> 00:09:01,937
Pulls itself out of its normal reaction to things.

76
00:09:02,738 --> 00:09:06,801
Accesses this point and see, oh, this is what's happening.

77
00:09:06,821 --> 00:09:10,865
Wanting, not wanting.

78
00:09:10,884 --> 00:09:15,288
And it's not as though a primary insight, it's not as though just seeing it once is enough.

79
00:09:15,927 --> 00:09:43,976
because the habit is so deeply ingrained in us it goes back a long way we have to believe Buddhist understanding goes back lifetimes so that's a really ingrained habit to indulge and reject indulge and be averse so we've got to keep seeing it keep seeing it and we won't pull ourselves off that sort of reaction unless we see the consequence and the consequence is

80
00:09:45,374 --> 00:10:14,638
unsatisfactoriness so when we indulge in something you can see that the indulgence is growing towards addiction and then you become obsessed with it so the suffering grows now when you come off it you have to go through the pain of renunciation the pain of letting it go now that's something else that we are beginning to understand that when you sit in meditation a lot of it is purgatory

81
00:10:15,985 --> 00:10:16,645
That's the way it is.

82
00:10:18,207 --> 00:10:20,350
And purgatory is different from hell.

83
00:10:21,772 --> 00:10:24,755
Hell is when you know there is no end to suffering.

84
00:10:24,775 --> 00:10:28,701
Purgatory, at least, you know there comes an end to it, even if it's the end of the meditation period.

85
00:10:30,403 --> 00:10:44,541
So it's a case of recognizing that to purge the heart, to actually cleanse the heart of these very clinging states, uncomfortable states, you have to suffer them.

86
00:10:44,857 --> 00:10:46,399
There's no way out of that.

87
00:10:48,903 --> 00:10:54,269
If you don't suffer them, and they're in the mind, it's not as though there's anywhere outside your mind.

88
00:10:54,729 --> 00:10:57,172
They remain in the mind as a turbulence.

89
00:10:57,192 --> 00:11:01,216
And that's when you get these psychosomatic illnesses, tics.

90
00:11:05,181 --> 00:11:06,062
They've nowhere to go.

91
00:11:06,101 --> 00:11:09,304
If there's anger in the system, where can it go?

92
00:11:11,748 --> 00:11:13,330
It's stuck there within the system.

93
00:11:13,681 --> 00:11:20,750
It's only when you let the anger out and feel it, and let it blow itself out, that there's a release of that energy.

94
00:11:21,412 --> 00:11:23,774
But remember, it's not just a simple release and gone.

95
00:11:24,515 --> 00:11:28,903
There's still the energy there, and that energy transforms into its opposite.

96
00:11:29,524 --> 00:11:31,446
So where there was hatred and anger, there's love.

97
00:11:31,767 --> 00:11:33,308
Where there was cruelty, compassion.

98
00:11:36,453 --> 00:11:40,278
You don't lose anything by the process of meditations.

99
00:11:41,153 --> 00:11:43,977
It's the same as what they say about energy in the universe.

100
00:11:43,998 --> 00:11:45,119
There's no energy lost.

101
00:11:45,139 --> 00:11:47,442
It always seems to be the same quantity of energy.

102
00:11:48,004 --> 00:11:52,932
It's just transforming, it's changing.

103
00:11:52,971 --> 00:12:02,407
One of the pleasant insights of meditation is that you don't have to do anything for your psychology.

104
00:12:02,547 --> 00:12:07,514
The psychology will heal itself because all it is is a turbulence, an energy.

105
00:12:09,065 --> 00:12:16,193
When we call it something, you see, whenever you give a name to something, it immediately substantiates it.

106
00:12:16,274 --> 00:12:18,456
It makes it into some sort of something solid.

107
00:12:19,317 --> 00:12:21,500
So you say to yourself, oh, I'm depressed.

108
00:12:21,520 --> 00:12:22,261
Well, there you are.

109
00:12:22,302 --> 00:12:23,484
You are depressed.

110
00:12:23,504 --> 00:12:24,083
You just said it.

111
00:12:25,285 --> 00:12:27,788
So I suffer from depression.

112
00:12:28,870 --> 00:12:30,011
Well, that's an object, isn't it?

113
00:12:30,072 --> 00:12:30,592
Depression.

114
00:12:30,633 --> 00:12:31,453
It's hard.

115
00:12:32,095 --> 00:12:33,856
How do you get over depressions?

116
00:12:35,086 --> 00:12:40,913
And it's only when you sit quietly with it and begin to investigate these feelings that you realize there's nothing at all.

117
00:12:40,974 --> 00:12:42,355
There's no such thing as depression.

118
00:12:43,096 --> 00:12:45,379
All there is is just this flow of sensations.

119
00:12:46,360 --> 00:12:46,841
That's all.

120
00:12:47,402 --> 00:12:54,871
And if you just stay long enough, four or five years, it begins to dissipate.

121
00:12:54,892 --> 00:12:56,914
So that's one of the problems of the mind.

122
00:12:57,596 --> 00:12:58,496
We need it, of course.

123
00:12:58,517 --> 00:13:00,820
We need to have concepts in ordinary daily life.

124
00:13:00,980 --> 00:13:01,760
That's not a problem.

125
00:13:03,202 --> 00:13:04,705
But it's to believe that they're real.

126
00:13:05,225 --> 00:13:14,136
So if I say to myself, you know, I suffer from depression, it's very difficult for me to see that that's just a mental concept.

127
00:13:14,957 --> 00:13:21,666
When I go into it, what I am actually suffering from are just heavy feelings, heavy sensations.

128
00:13:21,686 --> 00:13:26,732
And the mind is in a state of being blocked or unable to move.

129
00:13:28,635 --> 00:13:30,337
And that's fine, you see, if you stay with that.

130
00:13:31,418 --> 00:13:35,163
Then there's no pressure on yourself to become not depressed.

131
00:13:36,072 --> 00:13:38,235
There's no pressure to try and change anything.

132
00:13:38,816 --> 00:13:42,481
And so this turbulence that we have, what can it do?

133
00:13:43,182 --> 00:13:44,485
It just expresses itself.

134
00:13:45,466 --> 00:13:47,529
And in the expression, it blows itself out.

135
00:13:48,993 --> 00:14:02,433
And it's just that being able to be patient with mental states and to see them as just energy forms, forms of energy, you see, that allows them to dissipate.

136
00:14:04,051 --> 00:14:10,158
Now, we're not going to do that unless we are very clear that that's actually what's happening when we're in meditation.

137
00:14:11,419 --> 00:14:30,602
Because when you're in meditation, you might be sitting there and feeling these things like great restlessness, or tiredness and dullness in the head, the shaking of doubt, what the hell am I doing here, and all that sort of stuff.

138
00:14:30,623 --> 00:14:33,365
These hatreds, angers, greed, lusts, they're all

139
00:14:33,649 --> 00:14:34,730
They all come up, you see.

140
00:14:34,770 --> 00:14:42,099
Now when you sit in meditation and you access this point at the top of the comb, you're not suppressing anything.

141
00:14:43,019 --> 00:14:47,163
So it often feels that things are getting worse, much worse.

142
00:14:47,945 --> 00:14:55,451
And it's because sometimes for the first time in our lives, we're actually allowing this stuff to express itself fully within our consciousness.

143
00:14:58,595 --> 00:15:02,239
And if it does that, then often we get that reaction of fear or

144
00:15:02,505 --> 00:15:06,650
The meditation's making me more depressed.

145
00:15:06,671 --> 00:15:08,091
But it's not, honestly.

146
00:15:10,014 --> 00:15:16,542
What's happening is that the heart finally has that space and opportunity to express itself to you.

147
00:15:17,763 --> 00:15:20,206
So you thought you were sad, but you never thought you were this sad.

148
00:15:21,407 --> 00:15:25,552
You knew what grief was, but you didn't know it was painful as this.

149
00:15:27,653 --> 00:15:31,298
But if we can just have that courage, just that constancy,

150
00:15:31,716 --> 00:15:38,484
and to stay with it, and we won't get that unless we actually see this process as a healing process.

151
00:15:39,124 --> 00:15:39,945
That's important.

152
00:15:41,105 --> 00:15:57,302
So all the way during today, you see, for those of you who are new to this, to be aware that emotions are just arising and passing away, and if you don't indulge them, they pass away, and if you don't reject them, they come up a bit stronger, but they pass away.

153
00:15:58,024 --> 00:16:19,150
If we can see just in small little emotions that are rising constantly throughout the day, when something big comes up, something that we've suppressed, who knows from what time, then we'll have that knowledge which will give us the courage to just sit with it, to just stay with it, and just let it burn.

154
00:16:22,434 --> 00:16:24,817
Deep loneliness.

155
00:16:25,018 --> 00:16:25,938
People are lonely.

156
00:16:27,977 --> 00:16:29,480
You might feel yourself isolated.

157
00:16:31,443 --> 00:16:34,589
Our families dissipate, don't they?

158
00:16:34,609 --> 00:16:35,649
They go all over the place.

159
00:16:36,851 --> 00:16:39,096
Friendships, you move in and out of friendships.

160
00:16:39,596 --> 00:16:42,642
The society isn't static.

161
00:16:42,662 --> 00:16:44,865
So some people can feel terribly lonely.

162
00:16:46,467 --> 00:16:53,799
And when they sit with themselves, that loneliness can get really heavy.

163
00:16:54,269 --> 00:16:55,951
Because it's an existential loneliness.

164
00:16:55,991 --> 00:16:58,976
It's a feeling of, you know, like, why am I here in the first place?

165
00:16:59,157 --> 00:17:00,678
What's the point of being a human being?

166
00:17:01,681 --> 00:17:02,501
So it can dig deep.

167
00:17:02,562 --> 00:17:03,744
It can be a despair.

168
00:17:04,204 --> 00:17:05,666
It can lead you to a despair.

169
00:17:08,551 --> 00:17:10,615
So the meditation would open you up to that, you see.

170
00:17:10,634 --> 00:17:19,348
Now if you think that, well, loneliness leads to despair, leads to the bridge, then obviously there's no point in handling that.

171
00:17:19,368 --> 00:17:20,631
You may as well turn the TV on.

172
00:17:22,230 --> 00:17:32,000
But if you see that loneliness is just another mental state, and that if you just stay with it, it begins to dissipate, begins to just crack away and finally disappear.

173
00:17:32,662 --> 00:17:37,567
And if you can stay to the end point, you'll see that the other side of loneliness isn't despair at all.

174
00:17:37,768 --> 00:17:43,913
The other side is solitude, which is to be happy within oneself, just to be with oneself.

175
00:17:46,416 --> 00:17:52,103
So all these negative states, if we stay, even the little ones, if you stay with them long enough,

176
00:17:52,353 --> 00:18:10,410
and you see actually that they transform into their opposites, all the unwholesome stuff transforms into a wholesome state, then there grows that growing confidence in the process that's happening within us when we practice vipassana.

177
00:18:10,430 --> 00:18:19,238
Now, if we were just to do it for the sake of psychological benefit, we'd miss out, you see, on the spiritual side, which is the

178
00:18:19,858 --> 00:18:25,465
which is the undoing of that essential delusion in that which knows, in that which is looking.

179
00:18:27,428 --> 00:18:46,390
And to do that, just being aware of that process of reaction, wanting, not wanting, you see, is to release the delusion, to release us from the delusion that we can have permanent happiness in indulging in the world.

180
00:18:52,646 --> 00:19:21,422
and coupled with that is seeing that transience so when we really catch when we really catch the fact that everything is radically arising and passing away and we can't argue with the Buddha when he says that there's nothing in this world worth holding on to then you stop holding something comes, you win the lottery, great you lose all your money, great

181
00:19:22,027 --> 00:19:26,893
Be able just to, whatever arises, that's it.

182
00:19:27,334 --> 00:19:28,816
It arises, passes away, it's gone.

183
00:19:31,378 --> 00:19:38,607
And as we look at that, you see, then we're undermining this idea of a self, which goes at a much more subtle level.

184
00:19:39,689 --> 00:19:50,682
And without worrying about a concept of what does the self mean, rather to be concerned to understand how it manifests,

185
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:52,583
it manifests in control.

186
00:19:55,586 --> 00:19:57,588
The self wants to be in control.

187
00:19:57,788 --> 00:19:59,770
If it's in control, it's very happy.

188
00:20:00,372 --> 00:20:15,670
So if you've got a load of dosh in the bank, you're in control of all your financial needs and you can extend them all the way up to skiing in the Alps and stuff like that and then you feel you're in control of your life.

189
00:20:17,011 --> 00:20:18,814
If you've got power at work,

190
00:20:19,132 --> 00:20:26,084
And you're in charge of people and they're doing what you want and you're in control and you feel you're in control of your life.

191
00:20:27,806 --> 00:20:32,614
So it's that sense of control where you can catch the self.

192
00:20:32,875 --> 00:20:34,196
That obsessive control.

193
00:20:34,817 --> 00:20:36,059
Wanting to be in charge.

194
00:20:48,493 --> 00:21:00,291
So, coming down to our basic practice, we always begin by establishing that sense of calmness.

195
00:21:00,853 --> 00:21:03,017
Those seven factors that we went through quickly.

196
00:21:03,678 --> 00:21:06,221
And I'll do them again this evening in more detail.

197
00:21:06,301 --> 00:21:08,144
I'll explain them in more detail.

198
00:21:09,145 --> 00:21:15,556
And it's just getting that position and accessing that level, that point, the top of the cone, you see.

199
00:21:15,997 --> 00:21:16,257
And

200
00:21:16,574 --> 00:21:21,538
making that as a sort of self-reflection, making that as a recognition.

201
00:21:21,759 --> 00:21:25,623
Oh, now I'm in this position of the observer.

202
00:21:26,303 --> 00:21:27,805
I'm in this position of the witness.

203
00:21:28,384 --> 00:21:30,587
I'm in the position of the experiencer.

204
00:21:32,229 --> 00:21:35,412
To be very clear in our minds that this is the position I want to be in.

205
00:21:37,213 --> 00:21:44,421
And every time you lose it, you've wandered off somewhere or you're getting caught up in something, to immediately recognize that,

206
00:21:45,193 --> 00:21:46,736
and re-access this position.

207
00:21:48,038 --> 00:21:48,699
This we can do.

208
00:21:50,260 --> 00:21:56,150
We can make all sensations in the body quite objective, whether they're pleasant or unpleasant.

209
00:21:57,151 --> 00:21:59,394
We can actually feel as though they are there.

210
00:22:00,435 --> 00:22:11,893
Now, in the system of meditation that I teach, this Mahāsā, we actually use a little noting word, and that noting word is a great help just to distance from the object.

211
00:22:12,666 --> 00:22:23,901
So when there's discomfort, say, in the knee or from the posture, rather than moving away from it quickly, which is the usual thing that we do, you're always shifting about, you just catch yourself watching TV.

212
00:22:24,181 --> 00:22:25,363
You're always moving a bit.

213
00:22:27,325 --> 00:22:29,386
You can't stay in a position of discomfort.

214
00:22:30,229 --> 00:22:42,083
But here in the meditation, if you remain in that position of discomfort and you observe that discomfort, you stay with the discomfort, not to...

215
00:22:42,653 --> 00:22:51,506
react to it, you see, then you're maintaining and using that noting word, you see, pain, pain, pain, pain.

216
00:22:51,526 --> 00:22:56,554
And that helps you to keep yourself at the position on top of the cone.

217
00:22:58,916 --> 00:23:03,284
If you get an emotional state, you see, it could be a happy one, for heaven's sake.

218
00:23:04,144 --> 00:23:05,727
Something comes up, something joyful.

219
00:23:06,307 --> 00:23:07,670
So you notice it, joy.

220
00:23:07,931 --> 00:23:10,855
You don't get caught up in it, joyful, that must be good, let's get into it.

221
00:23:11,340 --> 00:23:19,568
See, and that means that you're now invested in a transient emotion.

222
00:23:19,588 --> 00:23:22,391
Because next minute you're depressed.

223
00:23:22,411 --> 00:23:23,792
One minute you're drunk.

224
00:23:23,813 --> 00:23:27,056
So you notice joy, you see, and it's there, oh joy, that's joy.

225
00:23:27,115 --> 00:23:27,695
Feel it.

226
00:23:28,317 --> 00:23:29,617
What's the texture of joy?

227
00:23:29,698 --> 00:23:31,720
What does the mind want to do when it's joyful?

228
00:23:32,299 --> 00:23:33,461
You don't get caught up in it.

229
00:23:35,063 --> 00:23:40,587
And as we remain at that position, you see, of the observer, the experiencer,

230
00:23:41,580 --> 00:23:50,069
we're beginning to develop a taste, a refined taste for equanimity, for peace.

231
00:23:51,511 --> 00:23:56,657
And eventually these things like joy and all that, they begin to feel a little gross.

232
00:24:00,201 --> 00:24:05,507
In Birmingham once, there was a young man came and it was the first time he'd ever meditated.

233
00:24:06,769 --> 00:24:10,692
And he came back the next week and he said, after that meditation period,

234
00:24:11,263 --> 00:24:40,443
and a few days meditation he couldn't listen to heavy rock anymore couldn't handle it it was too heavy and that's it you see it's that process of refinement and when we're at that level when we're at that level of the observer all those seven all those seven factors that we were experiencing a little bit this morning they're all there the calmness the steadiness of the watching the essential peace the silence

235
00:24:40,811 --> 00:25:08,220
there's no words in the observer and it's just getting acknowledging that you've got to acknowledge it oh this is where I am so okay that's a reflection it's a thought but it's a wise reflection it's this knowing coming to know how it got there and how it can maintain it and that's important because unless we're there we can't have these insights

236
00:25:12,182 --> 00:25:18,568
So now, finally, that position isn't the final position.

237
00:25:19,789 --> 00:25:28,958
Feeling ourselves to be the observer or the witness, knowing ourselves to be that, the feeler, the knower, isn't the final position because even there, there's somebody.

238
00:25:30,378 --> 00:25:31,460
I am feeling this.

239
00:25:31,760 --> 00:25:32,461
I know this.

240
00:25:32,861 --> 00:25:33,741
I can see this.

241
00:25:33,801 --> 00:25:34,663
There's still the I.

242
00:25:34,722 --> 00:25:37,346
There's still the knower.

243
00:25:37,365 --> 00:25:40,147
Now, you can't go beyond that by an act of will.

244
00:25:40,869 --> 00:25:44,233
because that's the point where the self comes to an end of itself.

245
00:25:45,895 --> 00:26:06,382
To come to the end of that, we have to keep doing that vipassana, doing that meditation, drawing ourselves through interest, through wanting to know, into a more refined, a more restricted moment, so that we're really beginning to center on sensations just as they arise and pass away.

246
00:26:07,923 --> 00:26:09,425
And it's doing that that

247
00:26:09,759 --> 00:26:14,646
that there's not the possibility of that reflection of I'm watching.

248
00:26:15,667 --> 00:26:17,211
The I begins to disappear.

249
00:26:17,270 --> 00:26:18,332
Well, it just disappears.

250
00:26:18,451 --> 00:26:19,354
It's not a process.

251
00:26:19,413 --> 00:26:25,021
It just disappears and suddenly there's just the watching, just the feeling, just the knowing.

252
00:26:26,042 --> 00:26:31,932
And that's those little points that there's what we can call true vipassana.

253
00:26:31,951 --> 00:26:34,915
And it's in those little moments that there are insights.

254
00:26:36,076 --> 00:26:37,219
The insight is not

255
00:26:37,434 --> 00:27:07,154
you know it's very very very rare for there to be some sort of cataclysmic world changing insight they're just little incremental insights which slowly build up over a period of time to change our view of things so that you wake up maybe a few years later and realise that hmm you've changed often often it's so subtle that other people see the change that you don't see it they say to you oh you've changed it can be as subtle as that

256
00:27:08,317 --> 00:27:21,789
So, keeping that in mind today, you see, to turn this day just into that very quiet, gentle process of observing ourselves, inwardly and outwardly.

257
00:27:21,809 --> 00:27:27,275
Just to take an interest in ourselves, just to take an interest in our psychology, in our bodies.

258
00:27:28,035 --> 00:27:29,336
What do we know of our bodies?

259
00:27:31,479 --> 00:27:33,440
Do you have any idea what's happening in your liver now?

260
00:27:35,442 --> 00:27:36,163
The clue, is it?

261
00:27:37,679 --> 00:27:38,881
you just hope it's all right.

262
00:27:41,124 --> 00:27:51,517
It's just that quiet, gentle, interested investigation of what's happening now, what is this, who am I, and all that sort of stuff.

263
00:27:52,939 --> 00:27:59,508
And just to slowly begin to recognize this position of the one who knows.

264
00:28:01,451 --> 00:28:07,077
And to do that, to quote Ajahn Tate, who is a very famous Thai teacher,

265
00:28:07,260 --> 00:28:08,281
Make it simple.

266
00:28:10,806 --> 00:28:11,626
Make it simple.

267
00:28:11,767 --> 00:28:12,327
Just watch.

268
00:28:13,348 --> 00:28:14,049
Take it easy.

269
00:28:15,230 --> 00:28:15,632
Relax.

270
00:28:15,692 --> 00:28:19,237
If you find yourself rushing, if you find yourself taking two steps at a time, stop.

271
00:28:20,417 --> 00:28:21,380
Come down the stairs again.

272
00:28:21,420 --> 00:28:21,920
Start again.

273
00:28:21,940 --> 00:28:25,285
If you find yourself gobbling, put the fork down.

274
00:28:25,744 --> 00:28:32,894
If you find yourself rushing everywhere, just stop.

275
00:28:32,914 --> 00:28:33,715
And then start again.

276
00:28:34,896 --> 00:28:35,377
Just keep

277
00:28:35,694 --> 00:28:38,156
Just keep bringing the energy down to calm.

278
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:52,971
If during the day this calmness is slipping into exhaustion and tiredness, then you'll have to judge for yourself whether it's something you have to take a rest with or something you just gently work against.

279
00:28:52,990 --> 00:29:02,799
Whether it really is true tiredness or just the good old, our two very good friends, my old teacher used to call them, sloth and torpor, right?

280
00:29:03,691 --> 00:29:33,579
remember if you indulge in sloth and torpor you just get more slothful and more torporous so be careful but if during the day you just feel that the heaviness is too much then take a rest but well again you have to judge for yourself you stay longer than 40 minutes you tend to you tend to disappear for a few hours make sure you put your alarm clock on so we can leave it at that

281
00:29:33,744 --> 00:29:35,465
and there's a bit of a walking period.

282
00:29:36,426 --> 00:29:39,529
So, unfortunately the weather isn't so clement.

283
00:29:40,089 --> 00:29:42,992
So, see if you can find a place to do some walking meditation.

284
00:29:45,755 --> 00:29:53,281
If you wish, you can also just read, or just reflect on your life, whatever takes your fancy.

285
00:29:54,782 --> 00:29:59,426
And we'll meet again for lunch.

